1
00:00:01,333 --> 00:00:05,166
<i>Captain's Log,</i>
<i>Stardate 44429.6.</i>

2
00:00:05,208 --> 00:00:08,542
<i>We are on a mapping survey</i>
<i>near the Cardassian sector.</i>

3
00:00:08,583 --> 00:00:11,583
<i>It has been nearly a year</i>
<i>since a peace treaty ended</i>

4
00:00:11,625 --> 00:00:14,500
<i>the long conflict between</i>
<i>the Federation and Cardassia.</i>

5
00:00:14,542 --> 00:00:16,583
Captain, we
are nearing

6
00:00:16,625 --> 00:00:20,959
the periphery
of Sector 21503.

7
00:00:21,041 --> 00:00:22,291
Be on the lookout

8
00:00:22,333 --> 00:00:23,667
for a Cardassian patrol ship,
Mr. Worf.

9
00:00:23,709 --> 00:00:25,125
They should be hailing
us soon.

10
00:00:25,166 --> 00:00:27,041
Even with the treaty,
they're still skittish

11
00:00:27,083 --> 00:00:29,500
about protecting
their border.

12
00:00:29,542 --> 00:00:31,875
Last time
I was in this sector

13
00:00:31,917 --> 00:00:33,500
I was on the<i> Stargazer</i>

14
00:00:33,542 --> 00:00:36,417
running at warp speed
ahead of a Cardassian warship.

15
00:00:36,458 --> 00:00:38,083
TROI:
Running,
Captain?

16
00:00:38,125 --> 00:00:40,041
You? That's hard to believe.

17
00:00:40,083 --> 00:00:41,500
Believe it.

18
00:00:41,542 --> 00:00:43,959
I'd been sent to make
preliminary overtures

19
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:46,625
to a truce, and I'd
lowered my shields

20
00:00:46,667 --> 00:00:48,542
as a gesture of goodwill.

21
00:00:48,583 --> 00:00:51,000
The Cardassians
were not impressed.

22
00:00:51,041 --> 00:00:53,291
They had taken out
most of my weapons

23
00:00:53,333 --> 00:00:56,750
and damaged the impulse engines
before I could regroup and run.

24
00:00:56,792 --> 00:00:59,125
The Cardassians have no honor.

25
00:00:59,166 --> 00:01:01,583
I do not trust them.

26
00:01:01,625 --> 00:01:03,667
They're our allies now,
Mr. Worf.

27
00:01:03,709 --> 00:01:05,166
We have to trust them.

28
00:01:05,208 --> 00:01:08,667
Trust is earned, not given away.

29
00:01:11,750 --> 00:01:13,542
I hope their scout ship
makes contact soon.

30
00:01:13,583 --> 00:01:16,750
It's not a good idea to stay
too long on a Cardassian border

31
00:01:16,792 --> 00:01:19,542
without making
your intentions known.

32
00:01:26,542 --> 00:01:28,875
What... what is it?

33
00:01:28,917 --> 00:01:33,125
Kelp buds, plankton loaf
and sea berries.

34
00:01:33,166 --> 00:01:34,917
Oh.

35
00:01:38,375 --> 00:01:40,291
Sweetheart

36
00:01:40,333 --> 00:01:42,542
I'm not a fish.

37
00:01:42,583 --> 00:01:44,083
It's very healthy.

38
00:01:44,125 --> 00:01:46,250
I had this every morning
when I was growing up.

39
00:01:46,291 --> 00:01:49,625
What? No muffins or oatmeal

40
00:01:49,667 --> 00:01:51,125
or corned beef
and eggs?

41
00:01:51,166 --> 00:01:52,375
For<i> breakfast?</i>

42
00:01:52,417 --> 00:01:54,917
Keiko

43
00:01:54,959 --> 00:01:56,625
I've been thinking.

44
00:01:56,667 --> 00:01:59,542
You've been introducing me
to all this wonderful food

45
00:01:59,583 --> 00:02:01,208
that you're
accustomed to.

46
00:02:01,250 --> 00:02:02,667
I'd like to do the same.

47
00:02:02,709 --> 00:02:04,709
Isn't that
what marriage is about?

48
00:02:04,750 --> 00:02:05,959
Sharing?

49
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:07,834
What kind of foods?

50
00:02:07,875 --> 00:02:10,875
Scalloped potatoes,
mutton shanks

51
00:02:10,917 --> 00:02:12,625
oxtails
and cabbage.

52
00:02:12,667 --> 00:02:14,125
Kind of heavy.

53
00:02:14,166 --> 00:02:17,417
Oh, you'll love it.
I promise.

54
00:02:17,458 --> 00:02:19,458
Oh, I can still remember
the aromas

55
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:20,959
when my mother was cooking.

56
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:22,875
She cooked?

57
00:02:22,917 --> 00:02:25,041
Oh, she didn't believe
in a replicator.

58
00:02:25,083 --> 00:02:27,875
She thought real food
was more nutritious.

59
00:02:27,917 --> 00:02:30,458
She handled real meat?

60
00:02:30,500 --> 00:02:31,875
She touched it and cut it?

61
00:02:31,917 --> 00:02:33,959
Yeah, like a master chef.

62
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:35,875
She was
fantastic.

63
00:02:35,917 --> 00:02:38,250
Of course,<i> I'll</i> have to use
the replicator.

64
00:02:38,291 --> 00:02:40,750
I'll make something special
for you tonight.

65
00:02:40,792 --> 00:02:43,041
You'll love it.
I promise.

66
00:02:43,083 --> 00:02:44,834
Okay.

67
00:02:44,875 --> 00:02:47,917
Maybe<i> I'll</i> have something
special for you tonight too.

68
00:02:47,959 --> 00:02:49,667
Mmm...

69
00:02:49,709 --> 00:02:50,667
(<i> both chuckling</i> )

70
00:02:50,709 --> 00:02:52,750
(<i> explosion</i> )

71
00:02:52,792 --> 00:02:53,709
Something's wrong.

72
00:02:53,750 --> 00:02:55,291
COMPUTER:
Red Alert.

73
00:02:55,333 --> 00:02:56,709
Take emergency stations.

74
00:02:56,750 --> 00:02:58,792
(<i> alarm blares</i> )

75
00:02:58,834 --> 00:03:01,458
Cardassian ship
preparing to
fire again, sir.

76
00:03:01,500 --> 00:03:03,542
Increase power
to the forward shields.

77
00:03:03,583 --> 00:03:05,875
(<i> explosion</i> )

78
00:03:05,917 --> 00:03:07,667
Hail them again,
Mr. Worf.

79
00:03:07,709 --> 00:03:09,542
What the hell
is he doing?
Damage report.

80
00:03:09,583 --> 00:03:11,417
Minor damage to
secondary hull

81
00:03:11,458 --> 00:03:13,000
before we put up
our shields, sir.

82
00:03:13,041 --> 00:03:15,959
No casualties.
Structural
integrity intact.

83
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:17,458
LA FORGE:
Engineering to Bridge.

84
00:03:17,500 --> 00:03:19,458
Starboard power coupling
is down.

85
00:03:19,500 --> 00:03:20,917
(<i> explosion</i> )

86
00:03:25,458 --> 00:03:27,125
Evasive action--
Delta sequence.

87
00:03:27,166 --> 00:03:28,458
Ready phasers, Mr. Worf.

88
00:03:28,500 --> 00:03:30,750
Delta evasion plan initiated.

89
00:03:30,792 --> 00:03:32,542
Limit targets
to engines and shields.

90
00:03:32,583 --> 00:03:34,041
WORF:
Aye, sir.

91
00:03:34,083 --> 00:03:35,583
Ready.

92
00:03:35,625 --> 00:03:37,417
Fire.

93
00:03:40,458 --> 00:03:42,000
Direct hit, sir.

94
00:03:42,041 --> 00:03:44,166
Moderate damage
to their aft shield generators.

95
00:03:44,208 --> 00:03:46,208
Continue phaser fire.

96
00:03:47,542 --> 00:03:49,458
DATA:
Multiple
hits, sir.

97
00:03:49,500 --> 00:03:52,291
Power failure
in their forward shields.

98
00:03:52,333 --> 00:03:53,291
WORF:
The Cardassian ship

99
00:03:53,333 --> 00:03:55,083
is standing down, sir.

100
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:58,166
Well, let's see
if they'll answer

101
00:03:58,208 --> 00:04:00,375
our hail now, Mr. Worf.

102
00:04:00,417 --> 00:04:02,166
Frequency open.

103
00:04:02,208 --> 00:04:03,792
This is Captain Jean-Luc Picard

104
00:04:03,834 --> 00:04:05,959
of the Federation
Starship<i> Enterprise.</i>

105
00:04:07,333 --> 00:04:12,583
I am Gul Macet,
of the Cardassian ship<i> Trager.</i>

106
00:04:12,625 --> 00:04:14,542
Why have you fired on us?

107
00:04:14,583 --> 00:04:16,834
A curious question, Captain.

108
00:04:16,875 --> 00:04:20,750
In war,
one attacks one's enemies.

109
00:04:20,792 --> 00:04:23,500
There is a treaty
between our peoples.

110
00:04:23,542 --> 00:04:27,625
Perhaps that fact was unknown
to the Federation starship

111
00:04:27,667 --> 00:04:31,417
which destroyed our space
station in the Cuellar system

112
00:04:31,458 --> 00:04:32,750
two days ago.

113
00:04:32,792 --> 00:04:34,750
Federation starship?

114
00:04:34,792 --> 00:04:39,083
Attacked an unarmed
science station.

115
00:04:39,125 --> 00:04:42,709
They had barely enough time
to send an emergency signal

116
00:04:42,750 --> 00:04:45,583
before they were incinerated.

117
00:04:45,625 --> 00:04:50,125
Gul Macet, the Federation
and the Cardassians

118
00:04:50,166 --> 00:04:52,917
have struggled too hard
for peace

119
00:04:52,959 --> 00:04:55,166
to abandon it so easily.

120
00:04:55,208 --> 00:04:59,834
We are not the ones
who have abandoned it, Captain.

121
00:04:59,875 --> 00:05:04,125
Let me talk to my superiors,
find out what is behind this.

122
00:05:04,166 --> 00:05:06,583
Give me one hour.

123
00:05:06,625 --> 00:05:08,458
The alternative is for us

124
00:05:08,500 --> 00:05:10,083
to continue firing
at one another.

125
00:05:10,125 --> 00:05:12,458
And in such a contest,
you would be

126
00:05:12,500 --> 00:05:14,792
at a disadvantage.

127
00:05:16,750 --> 00:05:18,875
Very well.

128
00:05:19,875 --> 00:05:22,875
<i>One</i> hour.

129
00:05:54,166 --> 00:05:58,709
<i>Space, the final frontier.</i>

130
00:05:58,750 --> 00:06:02,750
<i>These are the voyages</i>
<i>of the Starship</i> Enterprise.

131
00:06:02,792 --> 00:06:04,834
<i>Its continuing mission--</i>

132
00:06:04,875 --> 00:06:08,500
<i>to explore</i>
<i>strange new worlds</i>

133
00:06:08,542 --> 00:06:13,208
<i>to seek out new life</i>
<i>and new civilizations</i>

134
00:06:13,250 --> 00:06:17,583
<i>to boldly go</i>
<i>where no one has gone before.</i>

135
00:07:16,750 --> 00:07:19,792
Captain, we've confirmed
your report.

136
00:07:19,834 --> 00:07:21,917
It was the Starship<i> Phoenix</i>

137
00:07:21,959 --> 00:07:25,375
under the command
of Benjamin Maxwell.

138
00:07:25,417 --> 00:07:27,417
Ben Maxwell...

139
00:07:27,458 --> 00:07:29,417
but he's one of Starfleet's
finest Captains.

140
00:07:29,458 --> 00:07:32,375
He... he must have
had provocation.

141
00:07:32,417 --> 00:07:33,542
I wish we knew.

142
00:07:33,583 --> 00:07:35,333
He's gone on silent running.

143
00:07:35,375 --> 00:07:36,375
Doesn't answer

144
00:07:36,417 --> 00:07:37,542
our communiquÃ©s.

145
00:07:37,583 --> 00:07:39,500
Then he's still
in Cardassian space?

146
00:07:39,542 --> 00:07:43,583
The station he destroyed
was in Sector 21505.

147
00:07:43,625 --> 00:07:45,667
You're the nearest starship.

148
00:07:45,709 --> 00:07:48,792
We want you to go in
and find him.

149
00:07:48,834 --> 00:07:51,375
Will the Cardassians
cooperate?

150
00:07:51,417 --> 00:07:53,542
They've granted you
safe passage.

151
00:07:53,583 --> 00:07:55,834
We've agreed that you'll take
along a delegation

152
00:07:55,875 --> 00:07:59,000
of observers,
as a show of good faith.

153
00:08:00,834 --> 00:08:04,417
Jean-Luc, I don't have
to tell you

154
00:08:04,458 --> 00:08:10,291
the Federation is not prepared
for a new sustained conflict.

155
00:08:10,333 --> 00:08:12,709
You must preserve the peace

156
00:08:12,750 --> 00:08:15,625
no matter what the cost.

157
00:08:17,625 --> 00:08:19,583
Haden out.

158
00:08:26,291 --> 00:08:29,750
There will be three Cardassians
transporting aboard.

159
00:08:29,792 --> 00:08:32,000
Their Captain, Gul Macet,
and two of his aides.

160
00:08:32,041 --> 00:08:34,625
My intention is to be
as open as possible with them.

161
00:08:34,667 --> 00:08:37,208
Allow them to share
in our search for the<i> Phoenix.</i>

162
00:08:37,250 --> 00:08:38,834
Captain, it is necessary

163
00:08:38,875 --> 00:08:41,166
to assign them
a security detail.

164
00:08:41,208 --> 00:08:42,542
They're our guests, Mr. Worf.

165
00:08:42,583 --> 00:08:43,917
I don't want them to feel
like prisoners.

166
00:08:43,959 --> 00:08:45,625
RIKER:
I tend to agree with
Mr. Worf, Captain.

167
00:08:45,667 --> 00:08:48,208
I think we should limit their
access while they're on board.

168
00:08:48,250 --> 00:08:50,583
I don't think they need
to have the run of the ship.

169
00:08:50,625 --> 00:08:52,125
At least allow me
to post guards

170
00:08:52,166 --> 00:08:54,333
in some of the sensitive areas
of the ship.

171
00:08:54,375 --> 00:08:56,709
Very well.
Let's limit their access

172
00:08:56,750 --> 00:09:00,458
but you instruct your people
they are our guests.

173
00:09:00,500 --> 00:09:02,000
Aye, sir.

174
00:09:02,041 --> 00:09:03,375
Counselor,
I want you to stay

175
00:09:03,417 --> 00:09:04,667
as close to the crew
as possible.

176
00:09:04,709 --> 00:09:07,208
Some of them may feel
uncomfortable

177
00:09:07,250 --> 00:09:08,792
with Cardassians on board.

178
00:09:08,834 --> 00:09:10,500
I don't want any incidents.

179
00:09:10,542 --> 00:09:12,709
Yes, Captain.

180
00:09:12,750 --> 00:09:14,542
Mr. Data, is there
anyone else on board

181
00:09:14,583 --> 00:09:16,834
who served previously
with Captain Benjamin Maxwell?

182
00:09:16,875 --> 00:09:19,250
Accessing.

183
00:09:19,291 --> 00:09:21,667
Chief O'Brien served
under his command

184
00:09:21,709 --> 00:09:23,500
aboard the
<i>Rutledge,</i> sir.

185
00:09:23,542 --> 00:09:25,583
PICARD:
Indeed.

186
00:09:25,625 --> 00:09:28,583
Number One, will you
and the Counselor

187
00:09:28,625 --> 00:09:30,458
meet our guests
in Transporter Room Three?

188
00:09:30,500 --> 00:09:32,709
And inform Chief O'Brien
I will be calling on him.

189
00:09:32,750 --> 00:09:34,875
Yes, sir.

190
00:09:41,667 --> 00:09:43,750
RIKER:
Welcome
to the<i> Enterprise.</i>

191
00:09:43,792 --> 00:09:45,583
I'm First Officer
William Riker.

192
00:09:45,625 --> 00:09:48,166
Counselor Deanna Troi.

193
00:09:48,208 --> 00:09:50,583
I am Gul Macet.

194
00:09:50,625 --> 00:09:53,417
My aides, Glinn Daro

195
00:09:53,458 --> 00:09:55,000
Glinn Telle.

196
00:09:55,041 --> 00:09:56,792
RIKER:
This is
our Transporter Chief

197
00:09:56,834 --> 00:09:59,125
Mr. O'Brien.

198
00:10:01,458 --> 00:10:03,583
Shall we?

199
00:10:19,041 --> 00:10:20,542
<i>Captain's Log, supplemental.</i>

200
00:10:20,583 --> 00:10:22,542
<i>We have entered</i>
<i>Cardassian territory</i>

201
00:10:22,583 --> 00:10:25,959
<i>and are proceeding on our quest</i>
<i>to locate the</i> Phoenix.

202
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:27,417
And with long-range sensors

203
00:10:27,458 --> 00:10:30,625
we've been scanning a radius
of ten light-years.

204
00:10:30,667 --> 00:10:33,500
We can effectively scan
one sector a day.

205
00:10:33,542 --> 00:10:35,041
We're scanning
Sector 21505 now.

206
00:10:35,083 --> 00:10:36,208
And there's
still no sign

207
00:10:36,250 --> 00:10:38,000
of the<i> Phoenix.</i>

208
00:10:38,041 --> 00:10:40,542
In fact,
you have no assurance

209
00:10:40,583 --> 00:10:43,500
that the ship is still
in Sector 21505.

210
00:10:43,542 --> 00:10:45,750
In fact, we have no idea
where it is.

211
00:10:45,792 --> 00:10:47,667
We thought
the last known coordinates

212
00:10:47,709 --> 00:10:49,291
were a reasonably
good place

213
00:10:49,333 --> 00:10:51,959
to start.

214
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:53,542
Captain Picard

215
00:10:53,583 --> 00:10:57,500
you can understand
that we are skeptical.

216
00:10:57,542 --> 00:11:00,375
Do you expect us
to believe that
you are using

217
00:11:00,417 --> 00:11:04,166
every means at your disposal
to track down one of your own?

218
00:11:04,208 --> 00:11:07,041
Of course you are concerned,
Gul Macet.

219
00:11:07,083 --> 00:11:09,750
It is precisely
because of that fact

220
00:11:09,792 --> 00:11:12,125
that I have included you

221
00:11:12,166 --> 00:11:13,709
in every aspect
of our effort.

222
00:11:13,750 --> 00:11:15,208
You're present
with my staff.

223
00:11:15,250 --> 00:11:17,709
You're hearing
reports as
I hear them.

224
00:11:17,750 --> 00:11:21,041
Nothing edited,
nothing withheld.

225
00:11:21,083 --> 00:11:22,750
Very well.

226
00:11:22,792 --> 00:11:24,917
PICARD:
Transporter Chief
O'Brien served

227
00:11:24,959 --> 00:11:26,834
with Benjamin Maxwell.

228
00:11:26,875 --> 00:11:30,500
I thought that he might be able
to provide some insights.

229
00:11:30,542 --> 00:11:33,208
Mr. O'Brien,
I understand

230
00:11:33,250 --> 00:11:35,583
that Captain Maxwell lost
his family

231
00:11:35,625 --> 00:11:37,458
during a raid on an outpost.

232
00:11:37,500 --> 00:11:39,333
More like sabotage, sir.

233
00:11:39,375 --> 00:11:41,500
It was on Setlik III.

234
00:11:41,542 --> 00:11:46,083
A squad of Cardassian militia
made a sneak raid on an outpost.

235
00:11:46,125 --> 00:11:48,583
Wiped out close
to 100 civilians.

236
00:11:48,625 --> 00:11:51,291
Then it's revenge he's after.

237
00:11:51,333 --> 00:11:53,542
That's not what I meant.

238
00:11:53,583 --> 00:11:56,125
Maxwell is taking retribution
for his own loss.

239
00:11:56,166 --> 00:11:58,041
Captain Maxwell would never...

240
00:11:58,083 --> 00:12:00,542
Gentlemen, please, let's not
indulge in speculation.

241
00:12:00,583 --> 00:12:02,458
Can we confine

242
00:12:02,500 --> 00:12:05,041
our discussion
to the facts?

243
00:12:05,083 --> 00:12:06,583
Now, Mr. O'Brien...

244
00:12:06,625 --> 00:12:08,333
Worf to Captain Picard.

245
00:12:08,375 --> 00:12:09,750
Go ahead, Mr. Worf.

246
00:12:09,792 --> 00:12:13,000
Long-range sensors have located
the<i> Phoenix.</i>

247
00:12:13,041 --> 00:12:15,333
Gul Macet,
will you join me

248
00:12:15,375 --> 00:12:17,333
on the Bridge?

249
00:12:32,250 --> 00:12:33,500
Deck six.

250
00:12:33,542 --> 00:12:35,083
(<i> beeping</i> )

251
00:12:35,125 --> 00:12:36,208
Deck ten.

252
00:12:36,250 --> 00:12:37,667
(<i> beeping</i> )

253
00:12:45,959 --> 00:12:48,959
Your Captain is most impressive.

254
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:52,166
Yes, he is.

255
00:12:52,208 --> 00:12:54,625
Chief O'Brien

256
00:12:54,667 --> 00:12:57,625
our transporting system
is still operating

257
00:12:57,667 --> 00:12:59,875
with active feed
pattern buffers.

258
00:12:59,917 --> 00:13:03,291
I would like to talk with you
about your technology.

259
00:13:03,333 --> 00:13:04,458
I'll have to get

260
00:13:04,500 --> 00:13:07,041
Commander La Forge's
approval on that.

261
00:13:07,083 --> 00:13:09,583
I understand.

262
00:13:09,625 --> 00:13:11,375
In the meantime

263
00:13:11,417 --> 00:13:14,458
we're going
to your Ten-Forward.

264
00:13:14,500 --> 00:13:16,125
Will you join us?

265
00:13:18,125 --> 00:13:19,959
If my Commander tells me

266
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:24,041
to discuss the transporter
with you, I will.

267
00:13:24,083 --> 00:13:26,583
If Captain Picard orders me
to tell you everything I know

268
00:13:26,625 --> 00:13:30,667
about Ben Maxwell,
I will.

269
00:13:30,709 --> 00:13:34,208
But who I choose to
spend my free time with

270
00:13:34,250 --> 00:13:36,375
that's<i> my</i> business.

271
00:13:48,166 --> 00:13:52,500
Captain, the<i> Phoenix</i>
is in Sector 21505.

272
00:13:52,542 --> 00:13:54,417
Ensign, set a
course, warp six.

273
00:13:54,458 --> 00:13:56,625
Mr. Worf,
send a message by subspace.

274
00:13:56,667 --> 00:13:58,750
Tell them to prepare
for a rendezvous.

275
00:13:58,792 --> 00:13:59,709
Yes, Captain.

276
00:13:59,750 --> 00:14:01,750
Captain, a
suggestion?

277
00:14:01,792 --> 00:14:03,125
Yes.

278
00:14:03,166 --> 00:14:07,458
We have a number of
ships in Sector 21505.

279
00:14:07,500 --> 00:14:10,500
If you will give us
more precise coordinates

280
00:14:10,542 --> 00:14:13,917
and the ship's coded
transponder frequency

281
00:14:13,959 --> 00:14:16,458
we would be able
to intercept Maxwell

282
00:14:16,500 --> 00:14:18,542
far more quickly
than you.

283
00:14:18,583 --> 00:14:20,041
I'm sure that's true.

284
00:14:20,083 --> 00:14:22,500
However, given
the circumstances

285
00:14:22,542 --> 00:14:25,834
I would prefer to make
the initial contact myself.

286
00:14:25,875 --> 00:14:27,458
I'm sure<i> you</i> would

287
00:14:27,500 --> 00:14:28,917
if the situation
were reversed.

288
00:14:28,959 --> 00:14:31,750
Captain, time
is crucial.

289
00:14:31,792 --> 00:14:34,083
You have a dangerous
man out there

290
00:14:34,125 --> 00:14:37,125
with a huge arsenal
at his command.

291
00:14:37,166 --> 00:14:39,917
If he is intent upon
revenge against my people

292
00:14:39,959 --> 00:14:43,458
he must be stopped
before he can
do more damage.

293
00:14:43,500 --> 00:14:46,041
Captain, so far, we have
an isolated incident.

294
00:14:46,083 --> 00:14:47,458
If I can reach him first

295
00:14:47,500 --> 00:14:49,625
then perhaps
diplomacy can prevail

296
00:14:49,667 --> 00:14:53,000
but if one of your ships
should decide to retaliate

297
00:14:53,041 --> 00:14:55,959
there is a danger
we could lose control
of the situation.

298
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:00,041
Then you will not give
us the means to find
his precise location?

299
00:15:00,083 --> 00:15:02,166
No, I won't.

300
00:15:08,500 --> 00:15:10,291
O'BRIEN:
There you are.

301
00:15:10,333 --> 00:15:14,750
Potato casserole,
a dish fit for kings.

302
00:15:16,041 --> 00:15:20,083
