303
00:15:20,125 --> 00:15:22,875
(<i> humming</i> )

304
00:15:22,917 --> 00:15:24,792
What's that
you're singing?

305
00:15:24,834 --> 00:15:25,834
What?

306
00:15:25,875 --> 00:15:29,125
Oh, it's just an old song.

307
00:15:29,166 --> 00:15:32,417
A bunch of us used to sing it
together on the<i> Rutledge.</i>

308
00:15:32,458 --> 00:15:34,834
I hadn't thought
about it in years.

309
00:15:34,875 --> 00:15:36,500
What's it about?

310
00:15:36,542 --> 00:15:41,041
Oh, it's about
war and glory.

311
00:15:42,417 --> 00:15:46,583
âª The minstrel boy
to the war is gone âª

312
00:15:46,625 --> 00:15:51,417
âª In the ranks of death
you will find him âª

313
00:15:51,458 --> 00:15:55,750
âª His father's sword
he hath girded on âª

314
00:15:55,792 --> 00:16:01,542
âª And his wild harp
slung behind him. âª

315
00:16:01,583 --> 00:16:04,500
Captain Maxwell
always liked that song.

316
00:16:04,542 --> 00:16:07,458
I guess it's all this business
about him and the Cardassians

317
00:16:07,500 --> 00:16:09,834
brought it back
to me.

318
00:16:09,875 --> 00:16:13,959
You know, sitting
with the staff this morning

319
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:16,542
I could tell
there were people in that room

320
00:16:16,583 --> 00:16:17,583
who still don't like

321
00:16:17,625 --> 00:16:18,875
the Cardassians.

322
00:16:18,917 --> 00:16:21,625
I imagine
that's to be expected.

323
00:16:21,667 --> 00:16:23,166
You do?

324
00:16:23,208 --> 00:16:24,750
Sure, the war lasted
a long time.

325
00:16:24,792 --> 00:16:26,166
That takes its toll on people.

326
00:16:26,208 --> 00:16:28,208
What are these little,
dark things?

327
00:16:28,250 --> 00:16:30,417
Capers.

328
00:16:30,458 --> 00:16:32,500
But the fighting's over now.

329
00:16:32,542 --> 00:16:35,333
Why should anyone still feel...

330
00:16:35,375 --> 00:16:37,125
however they feel?

331
00:16:37,166 --> 00:16:39,834
You fought the Cardassians,
didn't you?

332
00:16:39,875 --> 00:16:43,000
Well, there were some skirmishes
when I was with Captain Maxwell.

333
00:16:43,041 --> 00:16:45,750
Well, how do<i> you</i> feel
about them?

334
00:16:45,792 --> 00:16:47,834
Me?

335
00:16:47,875 --> 00:16:49,542
Well, I feel fine.

336
00:16:49,583 --> 00:16:52,291
I mean, the war's over now.

337
00:16:57,959 --> 00:17:00,208
PICARD:
The pursuing ship
is the<i> Phoenix.</i>

338
00:17:00,250 --> 00:17:02,250
And the other?

339
00:17:02,291 --> 00:17:05,291
It appears to be
a Cardassian
supply ship.

340
00:17:05,333 --> 00:17:06,917
How would
you know that?

341
00:17:06,959 --> 00:17:10,542
We are able to make
that determination.

342
00:17:10,583 --> 00:17:13,625
You can read
our transponder codes.

343
00:17:13,667 --> 00:17:15,291
The important thing
at the moment

344
00:17:15,333 --> 00:17:17,166
is that one of your ships
may be in jeopardy.

345
00:17:17,208 --> 00:17:20,083
Mr. Worf, has there
been any answer to
our communication?

346
00:17:20,125 --> 00:17:24,208
No, Captain.
Put out a repeating message
on all subspace channels.

347
00:17:24,250 --> 00:17:25,667
Priority one communiquÃ©.

348
00:17:25,709 --> 00:17:26,750
Break off your pursuit
immediately.

349
00:17:26,792 --> 00:17:28,083
WORF:
Aye, sir.

350
00:17:28,125 --> 00:17:30,125
Gul Macet, you see
we are doing everything

351
00:17:30,166 --> 00:17:32,208
in our power
to reach the<i> Phoenix.</i>

352
00:17:32,250 --> 00:17:35,667
Yes, and accomplishing nothing,
I'm sorry to say.

353
00:17:35,709 --> 00:17:37,834
Can you show me the location

354
00:17:37,875 --> 00:17:39,166
of our other ships?

355
00:17:39,208 --> 00:17:40,542
Mr. Data?

356
00:17:42,333 --> 00:17:43,625
MACET:
There, you see?

357
00:17:43,667 --> 00:17:45,417
We have a warship
which could intercept

358
00:17:45,458 --> 00:17:47,375
the<i> Phoenix</i> before it's too late

359
00:17:47,417 --> 00:17:50,917
<i>if</i> you will give us
the transponder frequency.

360
00:17:50,959 --> 00:17:53,542
Or are you going
to stand there

361
00:17:53,583 --> 00:17:56,875
while our ship
is destroyed, Captain?

362
00:18:03,375 --> 00:18:05,083
Mr. Worf

363
00:18:05,125 --> 00:18:07,500
has there been
any response
to our hails?

364
00:18:08,709 --> 00:18:11,083
No, Captain.

365
00:18:14,375 --> 00:18:16,125
PICARD:
Very well.

366
00:18:18,333 --> 00:18:20,333
Mr. Worf...

367
00:18:25,500 --> 00:18:27,542
relay the prefix codes
of the<i> Phoenix</i>

368
00:18:27,583 --> 00:18:29,542
to the Cardassian warship.

369
00:18:29,583 --> 00:18:32,083
Sir, they
will be able

370
00:18:32,125 --> 00:18:33,458
to dismantle its shields.

371
00:18:33,500 --> 00:18:35,792
The<i> Phoenix</i>
will not have a chance.

372
00:18:35,834 --> 00:18:39,458
I cannot allow Maxwell
to ambush that supply ship.

373
00:18:41,375 --> 00:18:43,500
Mr. Worf, now!

374
00:18:45,125 --> 00:18:46,917
Yes, Captain.

375
00:18:59,875 --> 00:19:03,166
Sir, the Cardassian
warship is moving
on the<i> Phoenix.</i>

376
00:19:03,208 --> 00:19:04,959
Mr. Data, overlay

377
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:08,250
weapon ranges
of the two ships.

378
00:19:08,291 --> 00:19:11,583
The warship is 300,000
kilometers from the<i> Phoenix.</i>

379
00:19:11,625 --> 00:19:13,917
It is opening fire.

380
00:19:13,959 --> 00:19:16,125
The<i> Phoenix</i> has taken
a direct hit.

381
00:19:16,166 --> 00:19:19,834
The<i> Phoenix</i>
is beginning
evasive maneuvers.

382
00:19:19,875 --> 00:19:21,917
It has positioned
itself outside

383
00:19:21,959 --> 00:19:24,208
the weapons range
of the opposing ship.

384
00:19:25,959 --> 00:19:27,291
The<i> Phoenix</i> has
powered up

385
00:19:27,333 --> 00:19:30,458
both phasers and
photon torpedoes.

386
00:19:32,333 --> 00:19:35,709
The<i> Phoenix</i> is firing
photon torpedoes.

387
00:19:40,333 --> 00:19:43,250
He has destroyed our warship.

388
00:19:44,875 --> 00:19:47,250
Does the supply ship
have any weapons?

389
00:19:49,125 --> 00:19:50,709
Very limited.

390
00:19:50,750 --> 00:19:52,333
Certainly not enough

391
00:19:52,375 --> 00:19:55,458
to defeat
a Nebula-class starship.

392
00:19:55,500 --> 00:19:58,875
DATA:
Sir, the<i> Phoenix</i> is firing
on them.

393
00:19:58,917 --> 00:20:03,750
The warship carried
a crew of 600.

394
00:20:03,792 --> 00:20:06,792
The supply ship,
50.

395
00:20:06,834 --> 00:20:11,166
Mr. Data, estimated time
to intercept with the<i> Phoenix?</i>

396
00:20:11,208 --> 00:20:13,667
At our present speed
of warp four

397
00:20:13,709 --> 00:20:15,458
16 hours, 44 minutes.

398
00:20:15,500 --> 00:20:18,959
Ensign, increase
to warp nine.

399
00:20:33,291 --> 00:20:34,417
Captain.

400
00:20:34,458 --> 00:20:38,000
Chief, I wanted
to talk to you.

401
00:20:38,041 --> 00:20:39,959
Anything I can do, sir.
You know that.

402
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:42,041
Ben Maxwell--

403
00:20:42,083 --> 00:20:43,375
he must be quite a man.

404
00:20:43,417 --> 00:20:45,750
He's a rare
one, all right.

405
00:20:45,792 --> 00:20:47,625
I count myself
lucky, sir.

406
00:20:47,667 --> 00:20:50,875
I've served with the
two finest Captains
in Starfleet.

407
00:20:52,417 --> 00:20:55,291
From your knowledge
of the man

408
00:20:55,333 --> 00:20:57,583
what has gone wrong?

409
00:20:57,625 --> 00:20:59,542
Well, there's a reason
for what he's doing.

410
00:20:59,583 --> 00:21:01,834
Those Cardassians
were up to something.

411
00:21:01,875 --> 00:21:04,125
I'm sure of it.

412
00:21:04,166 --> 00:21:07,834
When his family was killed,
how did he take it?

413
00:21:07,875 --> 00:21:10,125
I'd say he took it well.

414
00:21:10,166 --> 00:21:12,625
Oh, I know
he was broken up inside.

415
00:21:12,667 --> 00:21:13,959
Who wouldn't be?

416
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:16,291
But you'd never
know it to see him.

417
00:21:16,333 --> 00:21:18,583
He never missed a minute's duty.

418
00:21:18,625 --> 00:21:21,166
Always had a smile, a joke.

419
00:21:21,208 --> 00:21:23,291
Hmm. I see.

420
00:21:23,333 --> 00:21:25,250
He would never
retaliate out
of vengeance

421
00:21:25,291 --> 00:21:27,333
no matter what
that Cardassian says

422
00:21:27,375 --> 00:21:29,333
They're up to
something, sir.

423
00:21:29,375 --> 00:21:31,917
They're the ones you
should be investigating

424
00:21:31,959 --> 00:21:33,208
not Captain Maxwell.

425
00:21:33,250 --> 00:21:35,208
You don't care for
the Cardassians.

426
00:21:35,250 --> 00:21:38,250
Oh, I like them fine.

427
00:21:38,291 --> 00:21:40,250
It's just...

428
00:21:40,291 --> 00:21:42,208
Well, I know them.

429
00:21:42,250 --> 00:21:45,000
You learn to watch
your back when you're
around those people.

430
00:21:45,041 --> 00:21:49,166
Ben Maxwell has just sent
more than 600 of them

431
00:21:49,208 --> 00:21:51,208
to their deaths.

432
00:21:51,250 --> 00:21:54,250
I don't know
what to say, sir

433
00:21:54,291 --> 00:21:56,375
but he must have had
his reasons.

434
00:21:56,417 --> 00:21:59,250
(<i> sighs</i> )

435
00:21:59,291 --> 00:22:01,542
I think...

436
00:22:01,583 --> 00:22:03,875
when one has been angry
for a very long time

437
00:22:03,917 --> 00:22:05,166
one gets used to it.

438
00:22:05,208 --> 00:22:06,834
And it becomes
comfortable

439
00:22:06,875 --> 00:22:10,125
like...
like old leather.

440
00:22:11,250 --> 00:22:14,166
And finally...

441
00:22:14,208 --> 00:22:15,709
it becomes so familiar

442
00:22:15,750 --> 00:22:18,959
that one can't ever remember
feeling any other way.

443
00:22:21,291 --> 00:22:23,208
Thank you, Chief.

444
00:22:44,250 --> 00:22:46,250
<i>Kanar.</i>

445
00:22:52,291 --> 00:22:54,250
Mind if I join you?

446
00:22:56,417 --> 00:22:58,375
You want another?

447
00:23:00,166 --> 00:23:02,250
And an ale.

448
00:23:04,667 --> 00:23:07,208
<i>Kanar.</i>

449
00:23:07,250 --> 00:23:10,583
I never could develop
a taste for it.

450
00:23:10,625 --> 00:23:13,583
It takes a bit
of getting used to.

451
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:18,792
I wanted to say I...

452
00:23:18,834 --> 00:23:20,333
I owe you an apology.

453
00:23:20,375 --> 00:23:23,000
I shouldn't have
popped off like that

454
00:23:23,041 --> 00:23:24,458
in the turbolift.

455
00:23:24,500 --> 00:23:25,750
I think...

456
00:23:25,792 --> 00:23:27,959
Here's your ale,
Mr. O'Brien.

457
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:31,417
This has been hard
on all of us.

458
00:23:31,458 --> 00:23:33,166
I know I'll be happy

459
00:23:33,208 --> 00:23:35,917
when I'm back
on my own ship.

460
00:23:35,959 --> 00:23:37,542
I guess that's true.

461
00:23:37,583 --> 00:23:39,917
I hadn't thought
about that.

462
00:23:42,583 --> 00:23:45,625
I was on Setlik III
with Captain Maxwell

463
00:23:45,667 --> 00:23:47,875
the morning after
the massacre.

464
00:23:49,875 --> 00:23:52,834
We were too late,
of course.

465
00:23:52,875 --> 00:23:54,959
(<i> sighs</i> )

466
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:56,625
Almost everyone was dead.

467
00:23:56,667 --> 00:23:59,625
That was a terrible mistake.

468
00:23:59,667 --> 00:24:03,208
We were told the outpost
was a launching place

469
00:24:03,250 --> 00:24:04,917
for a massive attack

470
00:24:04,959 --> 00:24:06,417
against us.

471
00:24:08,333 --> 00:24:11,667
The only people left alive

472
00:24:11,709 --> 00:24:14,417
were in an outlying
district of the settlement.

473
00:24:14,458 --> 00:24:17,959
I was sent there
with a squad to
reinforce them.

474
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:21,875
The Cardassians
were advancing on us...

475
00:24:21,917 --> 00:24:27,041
moving through the streets,
destroying, killing.

476
00:24:27,083 --> 00:24:29,667
I was with a group
of women and children

477
00:24:29,709 --> 00:24:33,417
when two Cardassian soldiers
burst in.

478
00:24:33,458 --> 00:24:35,458
I stunned one of them.

479
00:24:35,500 --> 00:24:37,417
The other one jumped me.

480
00:24:37,458 --> 00:24:40,208
We struggled.

481
00:24:40,250 --> 00:24:42,709
One of the women threw me
a phaser

482
00:24:42,750 --> 00:24:45,667
and I fired.

483
00:24:55,041 --> 00:24:58,208
The phaser was set at maximum.

484
00:24:58,250 --> 00:25:00,625
The man just...

485
00:25:00,667 --> 00:25:03,709
just incinerated there

486
00:25:03,750 --> 00:25:06,208
before my eyes.

487
00:25:06,250 --> 00:25:10,166
I'd never killed
anything before.

488
00:25:10,208 --> 00:25:12,125
When I was a kid

489
00:25:12,166 --> 00:25:16,166
I'd worry
about swatting a mosquito.

490
00:25:22,166 --> 00:25:25,583
It's not<i> you</i> I hate, Cardassian.

491
00:25:25,625 --> 00:25:28,083
I hate what<i> I</i> became

492
00:25:28,125 --> 00:25:30,083
because of you.

493
00:25:35,125 --> 00:25:37,875
(<i> door opens, closes</i> )

494
00:25:40,583 --> 00:25:42,917
I will protest
this, Klingon.

495
00:25:42,959 --> 00:25:45,000
Lieutenant?

496
00:25:45,041 --> 00:25:47,917
He was found
at a computer station on deck 35

497
00:25:47,959 --> 00:25:50,417
attempting to access information
on<i> our</i> weapons systems.

498
00:25:50,458 --> 00:25:52,834
TELLE:
A lie,
Gul Macet.

499
00:25:52,875 --> 00:25:55,333
I was studying
the terminal
interface systems.

500
00:25:55,375 --> 00:25:57,291
They're more
efficient
than ours.

501
00:25:57,333 --> 00:26:00,875
I have no idea
what was in
the files.

502
00:26:02,458 --> 00:26:04,875
What business did you have

503
00:26:04,917 --> 00:26:07,500
going near
one of their computers?

504
00:26:09,709 --> 00:26:12,417
But, Gul Macet,
I meant nothing.

505
00:26:12,458 --> 00:26:14,166
There was no harm done.

506
00:26:14,208 --> 00:26:16,542
Go to your quarters.

507
00:26:16,583 --> 00:26:18,250
You're confined there

508
00:26:18,291 --> 00:26:20,750
for the duration
of this expedition.

509
00:26:20,792 --> 00:26:23,166
As you wish.

510
00:26:23,208 --> 00:26:24,583
Sir.

511
00:26:26,208 --> 00:26:28,500
PICARD:
Mr. Worf,
please accompany him.

512
00:26:28,542 --> 00:26:30,500
WORF:
Gladly, Captain.

513
00:26:38,625 --> 00:26:44,083
Captain, may we
speak in private?

514
00:26:44,125 --> 00:26:46,667
You have the Bridge,
Number One.

515
00:26:56,834 --> 00:26:57,959
(<i> sighs</i> )

516
00:26:58,000 --> 00:26:59,125
I deeply regret

517
00:26:59,166 --> 00:27:01,250
what my aide
has done, Captain.

518
00:27:01,291 --> 00:27:03,875
You have my word
he will be disciplined

519
00:27:03,917 --> 00:27:05,208
upon my return.

520
00:27:05,250 --> 00:27:07,583
You may take whatever action
against him

521
00:27:07,625 --> 00:27:08,583
you feel is appropriate.

522
00:27:08,625 --> 00:27:10,041
I consider the matter closed.

523
00:27:10,083 --> 00:27:12,834
I'm not sure
I would be so generous

524
00:27:12,875 --> 00:27:14,583
in your place, Captain.

525
00:27:14,625 --> 00:27:16,208
Thank you.

526
00:27:16,250 --> 00:27:18,625
If there is to be
a lasting peace, Gul Macet

527
00:27:18,667 --> 00:27:22,166
neither you nor I must allow
any one man

528
00:27:22,208 --> 00:27:24,375
to undermine
our efforts.

529
00:27:32,625 --> 00:27:36,166
There are those who...

530
00:27:36,208 --> 00:27:38,417
crave war--

531
00:27:38,458 --> 00:27:40,834
who need it.

532
00:27:40,875 --> 00:27:43,834
I am not one of them, Captain

533
00:27:43,875 --> 00:27:47,000
and I'm beginning to see

534
00:27:47,041 --> 00:27:49,208
that neither are you.

535
00:27:49,250 --> 00:27:52,500
We have had
our full measure.

536
00:27:52,542 --> 00:27:56,208
The lasting peace begins here

537
00:27:56,250 --> 00:27:58,625
with the two of us.

538
00:27:58,667 --> 00:28:00,542
DATA:
Bridge to Captain.

539
00:28:00,583 --> 00:28:02,166
Picard here.

540
00:28:02,208 --> 00:28:04,083
We have located
the<i> Phoenix,</i> sir.

541
00:28:04,125 --> 00:28:06,625
We will intercept it
in 22 minutes.

542
00:28:16,333 --> 00:28:19,542
<i>Captain's Log,</i>
<i>Stardate 44431.7.</i>

543
00:28:19,583 --> 00:28:20,792
<i>We have established</i>
<i>communication</i>

544
00:28:20,834 --> 00:28:22,208
<i>with Captain Maxwell</i>

545
00:28:22,250 --> 00:28:25,083
<i>and he has agreed</i>
<i>to come on board.</i>

546
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:31,417
Welcome aboard, sir.

547
00:28:31,458 --> 00:28:33,333
I'm Commander Riker,
First Officer.

548
00:28:33,375 --> 00:28:35,417
I know all about
you, Commander.

549
00:28:35,458 --> 00:28:37,917
Fine work you did
with the Borg.

550
00:28:37,959 --> 00:28:39,375
We all owe you
on that one.

551
00:28:39,417 --> 00:28:40,959
Thank you, sir.

552
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:42,208
O'Brien?

553
00:28:42,250 --> 00:28:44,250
Miles O'Brien?

554
00:28:44,291 --> 00:28:46,166
Hello, Captain.

555
00:28:46,208 --> 00:28:48,333
Good to see
you again.
How are you?

556
00:28:48,375 --> 00:28:50,792
I had no idea you were
on the<i> Enterprise.</i>

557
00:28:50,834 --> 00:28:52,583
This was my tactical officer
on the<i> Rutledge.</i>

558
00:28:52,625 --> 00:28:54,333
Best I ever had.

559
00:28:54,375 --> 00:28:55,458
Thank you, sir.

560
00:28:55,500 --> 00:28:57,166
O'Brien has
the ability

561
00:28:57,208 --> 00:28:59,500
to size up a situation instantly

562
00:28:59,542 --> 00:29:02,875
then come up with options
to fit all contingencies.

563
00:29:02,917 --> 00:29:05,542
Remarkable!
Well, if that's true,
I learned it from you, sir.

564
00:29:05,583 --> 00:29:08,041
(<i> in Irish brogue</i> ):
But you got that silver tongue

565
00:29:08,083 --> 00:29:09,250
by kissing the stone

566
00:29:09,291 --> 00:29:12,792
right?

567
00:29:12,834 --> 00:29:16,166
Well, Commander, best I see
your Captain straight away.

568
00:29:16,208 --> 00:29:18,208
We've got a lot to talk about.

569
00:29:18,250 --> 00:29:19,959
Yes, sir.

570
00:29:35,709 --> 00:29:37,625
Captain Jean-Luc Picard

571
00:29:37,667 --> 00:29:39,750
Captain Benjamin Maxwell.

572
00:29:39,792 --> 00:29:42,250
That will be
all, Commander.

573
00:29:44,291 --> 00:29:45,458
Captain.

574
00:29:45,500 --> 00:29:47,041
A pleasure, Captain.

575
00:29:47,083 --> 00:29:49,041
Please sit down.

576
00:29:51,667 --> 00:29:54,375
You must think
I've gone mad.

577
00:29:56,458 --> 00:29:58,709
The thought
had occurred.

578
00:29:58,750 --> 00:30:01,792
Picard, I have to tell you.

579
00:30:01,834 --> 00:30:04,333
I was grateful
when I realized it was<i> you</i>

580
00:30:04,375 --> 00:30:05,959
Starfleet had sent after me--

581
00:30:06,000 --> 00:30:08,208
someone who knows
what it's really
like out here.

582
00:30:08,250 --> 00:30:11,375
I know of nothing out here
that could possibly justify

583
00:30:11,417 --> 00:30:13,417
what you
have done.

584
00:30:13,458 --> 00:30:15,625
Then listen to this.

585
00:30:15,667 --> 00:30:18,667
The Cardassians
are arming again.

586
00:30:18,709 --> 00:30:20,792
That so-called
science station?

587
00:30:20,834 --> 00:30:23,834
Military supply port.

588
00:30:23,875 --> 00:30:25,291
How do you know this?

589
00:30:25,333 --> 00:30:27,417
Information comes my way.

590
00:30:27,458 --> 00:30:29,250
From whom?

591
00:30:29,291 --> 00:30:31,041
Where is your documentation?

592
00:30:31,083 --> 00:30:32,792
I know
what they're doing!

593
00:30:32,834 --> 00:30:36,000
I can smell it.

594
00:30:37,417 --> 00:30:39,625
There's no good reason
for a science station

595
00:30:39,667 --> 00:30:41,333
in the Cuellar system.

596
00:30:41,375 --> 00:30:43,375
But it's
a hell of a strategic site

597
00:30:43,417 --> 00:30:45,458
for a military
transport station--

598
00:30:45,500 --> 00:30:49,333
a jumping-off point
into three Federation sectors.

599
00:30:49,375 --> 00:30:51,542
They're running
supply ships
back and forth.

600
00:30:51,583 --> 00:30:54,875
And nobody's going to tell me
it's for scientific research.

601
00:30:54,917 --> 00:30:57,500
But whatever circumstances
you encountered

602
00:30:57,542 --> 00:30:59,208
why didn't you notify Starfleet?

603
00:30:59,250 --> 00:31:02,166
(<i> scoffs</i> ):
And wait six months

604
00:31:02,208 --> 00:31:04,458
while the bureaucrats
sit around reading reports

605
00:31:04,500 --> 00:31:07,959
trying to figure out
what to do?

606
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:11,041
They don't know
what's going on out here.

607
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:15,083
But you should, Picard.

608
00:31:15,125 --> 00:31:18,125
You know what it's like
to be under fire.

609
00:31:18,166 --> 00:31:19,959
You weren't under fire.

610
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:21,542
Lives were at stake.

611
00:31:21,583 --> 00:31:22,500
Whose lives?

612
00:31:22,542 --> 00:31:24,542
We had to act now!

613
00:31:24,583 --> 00:31:25,959
Why?

614
00:31:29,917 --> 00:31:33,083
Smells musty in here...

615
00:31:33,125 --> 00:31:36,291
like a bureaucrat's office.

616
00:31:36,333 --> 00:31:39,166
You have killed
nearly 700 people

617
00:31:39,208 --> 00:31:42,625
and you have taken us
to the brink of war.

618
00:31:42,667 --> 00:31:44,291
I have prevented war

619
00:31:44,333 --> 00:31:47,458
or at the very least delayed it
a good long time.

620
00:31:47,500 --> 00:31:51,583
The peace treaty was a ruse,
to give them breathing room

621
00:31:51,625 --> 00:31:53,208
time to regroup.

622
00:31:53,250 --> 00:31:55,667
And so, all alone, you decided
to dispose of the treaty.

623
00:31:55,709 --> 00:31:57,500
I took the initiative.

624
00:31:57,542 --> 00:31:59,542
I did what had to be done.

625
00:31:59,583 --> 00:32:01,375
What had to be done?

626
00:32:01,417 --> 00:32:04,166
Hmm? For whom?

627
00:32:04,208 --> 00:32:05,750
Why would a man

628
00:32:05,792 --> 00:32:09,041
with a long
and brilliant service

629
00:32:09,083 --> 00:32:11,166
abandon
the fundamental principles

630
00:32:11,208 --> 00:32:13,583
that he has believed in--
even fought for--

631
00:32:13,625 --> 00:32:16,333
all of his life?

632
00:32:16,375 --> 00:32:17,917
Well, I believe

633
00:32:17,959 --> 00:32:21,000
it is because of what they did
to your wife

634
00:32:21,041 --> 00:32:21,959
and your children.

635
00:32:22,000 --> 00:32:23,542
Not true...
not true.

636
00:32:23,583 --> 00:32:26,125
To avenge
their deaths.

637
00:32:31,291 --> 00:32:35,041
You're a fool, Picard.

638
00:32:35,083 --> 00:32:39,041
History will look at you
and say, "This man was a fool."

639
00:32:40,166 --> 00:32:42,792
I'll accept the judgment
of history.

640
00:32:42,834 --> 00:32:46,458
When it becomes clear
what the Cardassians have done

641
00:32:46,500 --> 00:32:48,417
I will be vindicated.

642
00:32:48,458 --> 00:32:52,375
What the Cardassians have
or have not done is irrelevant.

643
00:32:52,417 --> 00:32:55,250
Irrelevant?!

644
00:32:55,291 --> 00:32:57,083
Then come with me.

645
00:32:57,125 --> 00:32:58,208
Find one of their supply ships

646
00:32:58,250 --> 00:32:59,208
and we'll see

647
00:32:59,250 --> 00:33:02,250
how "irrelevant"
it is.

648
00:33:02,291 --> 00:33:03,792
We're not going after

649
00:33:03,834 --> 00:33:06,041
any more
Cardassian ships.

650
00:33:06,083 --> 00:33:09,417
You're going
to return to your Bridge

651
00:33:09,458 --> 00:33:14,083
and set a course
for Starbase 211.

652
00:33:14,125 --> 00:33:16,250
The<i> Phoenix</i> and the
<i>Enterprise</i> will return

653
00:33:16,291 --> 00:33:18,583
to Federation
space together.

654
00:33:18,625 --> 00:33:20,458
Those are
Starfleet's orders.

655
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:25,291
I will permit
you the dignity

656
00:33:25,333 --> 00:33:28,750
of retaining your command
during the voyage

657
00:33:28,792 --> 00:33:32,458
but the only alternative
is to put you in the brig

658
00:33:32,500 --> 00:33:35,917
and to tow your ship back
to the Starbase in disgrace.

659
00:33:42,083 --> 00:33:44,583
I will return to my ship.

660
00:33:44,625 --> 00:33:48,041
You understand
your orders?

661
00:33:48,083 --> 00:33:50,000
Yes, Captain.

662
00:33:50,041 --> 00:33:53,417
Mr. Worf, report
to my ready room.

663
00:33:53,458 --> 00:33:55,208
My guest is departing.

664
00:33:55,250 --> 00:33:57,291
Aye, sir.

665
00:34:07,250 --> 00:34:08,750
<i>Captain's Log, supplemental.</i>

666
00:34:08,792 --> 00:34:10,542
<i>With the</i> Phoenix
<i>in close formation</i>

667
00:34:10,583 --> 00:34:14,291
<i>we are proceeding directly</i>
<i>to Starbase 211.</i>

668
00:34:14,333 --> 00:34:16,959
Mr. Data, how long until
we clear Cardassian space?

669
00:34:17,000 --> 00:34:18,291
At our present speed

670
00:34:18,333 --> 00:34:20,208
three hours,
20 minutes, sir.

671
00:34:20,250 --> 00:34:22,625
Mr. Worf, send a message
to Admiral Haden at Starfleet.

672
00:34:22,667 --> 00:34:24,625
Inform them of
our projected time of arrival.

673
00:34:24,667 --> 00:34:27,083
Aye, sir.

674
00:34:27,125 --> 00:34:30,709
Captain, the<i> Phoenix</i>
has changed course.

675
00:34:35,667 --> 00:34:38,041
What is he doing?

676
00:34:38,083 --> 00:34:40,125
Ensign, change course to pursue.

677
00:34:40,166 --> 00:34:42,041
(<i> sighs</i> )

678
00:34:42,083 --> 00:34:44,959
Mr. Worf, will you hail
Captain Maxwell?

679
00:34:45,000 --> 00:34:47,959
No response, Captain.

680
00:34:48,000 --> 00:34:50,041
Data, project his new course.

681
00:34:50,083 --> 00:34:52,458
The<i> Phoenix</i> is headed directly
for a Cardassian vessel

682
00:34:52,500 --> 00:34:54,500
.12 light-years
from our location.

683
00:34:54,542 --> 00:34:58,166
He'll attack that ship,
just as he did the others.

684
00:34:58,208 --> 00:34:59,959
PICARD:
Continue the hail,
Mr. Worf.

685
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:02,375
Priority one message.

686
00:35:02,417 --> 00:35:05,083
Do you know
what that ship might be?

687
00:35:05,125 --> 00:35:08,291
I imagine it's a supply ship

688
00:35:08,333 --> 00:35:11,417
headed for the research station
in the Kelrabi system.

689
00:35:11,458 --> 00:35:14,291
The<i> Phoenix</i> still
does not respond, sir.

690
00:35:14,333 --> 00:35:16,583
Ensign, warp eight.
Overtake him.

691
00:35:16,625 --> 00:35:20,166
Captain, the<i> Phoenix</i> has
accelerated to warp nine.

692
00:35:20,208 --> 00:35:21,500
We will not be able to reach him

693
00:35:21,542 --> 00:35:23,041
before he intercepts
the Cardassian vessel.

694
00:35:23,083 --> 00:35:24,458
Ensign, warp nine.

695
00:35:24,500 --> 00:35:26,000
Aye, sir.

696
00:35:26,041 --> 00:35:27,709
Mr. Worf, arm phasers.

697
00:35:27,750 --> 00:35:28,667
Continue the hail.

698
00:35:28,709 --> 00:35:30,458
Aye, sir.

699
00:35:30,500 --> 00:35:33,375
Captain, Chief O'Brien was
Maxwell's tactical officer.

700
00:35:33,417 --> 00:35:36,166
Get him up here.

701
00:35:40,208 --> 00:35:42,417
DATA:
Sir, the<i> Phoenix</i> has
dropped out of warp.

702
00:35:42,458 --> 00:35:44,709
They have reached
the Cardassian vessel.

703
00:35:44,750 --> 00:35:46,291
RIKER:
Slow to impulse.

704
00:35:46,333 --> 00:35:48,208
Vessels are within visual range.

705
00:35:48,250 --> 00:35:49,834
On screen.

706
00:35:51,792 --> 00:35:52,917
RIKER:
Has the<i> Phoenix</i>

707
00:35:52,959 --> 00:35:53,875
activated
its weapons systems?

708
00:35:53,917 --> 00:35:55,166
DATA:
Negative, sir.

709
00:35:55,208 --> 00:35:57,083
Their phaser banks
are not armed.

710
00:35:57,125 --> 00:35:58,625
What about
the Cardassians?

711
00:35:58,667 --> 00:36:01,208
Sensors are unable
to determine the status

712
00:36:01,250 --> 00:36:03,333
of the Cardassian
defensive systems.

713
00:36:03,375 --> 00:36:07,583
Their ship is running
with a high-powered
subspace field.

714
00:36:10,417 --> 00:36:13,834
Mr. O'Brien,
your former Commander

715
00:36:13,875 --> 00:36:15,750
a Federation Captain,
is about to place me

716
00:36:15,792 --> 00:36:17,667
in the position
of firing on his ship.

717
00:36:17,709 --> 00:36:19,625
I need your knowledge
of the man

718
00:36:19,667 --> 00:36:22,667
how he thinks,
what he's capable of doing.

719
00:36:22,709 --> 00:36:23,834
Aye, sir.

720
00:36:23,875 --> 00:36:26,625
Sir, Captain Maxwell
is hailing us.

721
00:36:26,667 --> 00:36:28,959
On screen.

722
00:36:30,041 --> 00:36:31,959
MAXWELL:
All right, Picard.

723
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:35,041
You need proof?
You've got it now.

724
00:36:35,083 --> 00:36:38,208
Captain Maxwell, you have
disobeyed a direct order.

725
00:36:38,250 --> 00:36:39,750
Board the ship.

726
00:36:39,792 --> 00:36:42,542
You'll see that everything
I've been saying is true.

727
00:36:42,583 --> 00:36:45,417
The Cardassian vessel
will not be boarded.

728
00:36:45,458 --> 00:36:49,083
You will transport yourself
aboard the<i> Enterprise.</i>

729
00:36:49,125 --> 00:36:53,166
Picard, if you don't board
that ship

730
00:36:53,208 --> 00:36:55,083
I'll destroy it.

731
00:36:55,125 --> 00:36:58,291
And I will use
whatever force is necessary

732
00:36:58,333 --> 00:37:01,583
to prevent you from taking
that action, Captain.

733
00:37:05,500 --> 00:37:08,041
Sir, Captain Maxwell--

734
00:37:08,083 --> 00:37:09,709
if he feels his back
is against the wall

735
00:37:09,750 --> 00:37:11,166
he'll strike.

736
00:37:11,208 --> 00:37:13,834
Captain, the<i> Phoenix</i>
is transferring power

737
00:37:13,875 --> 00:37:14,875
to its shields.

738
00:37:14,917 --> 00:37:16,083
WORF:
They are arming phasers

739
00:37:16,125 --> 00:37:18,000
and loading forward
torpedo bays.

740
00:37:18,041 --> 00:37:19,291
Red Alert.

741
00:37:19,333 --> 00:37:20,792
Seems you were right,
Mr. O'Brien.

742
00:37:20,834 --> 00:37:22,625
Ready phasers,
load torpedoes.

743
00:37:22,667 --> 00:37:23,792
Phasers armed.

744
00:37:23,834 --> 00:37:25,875
Loading forward and
aft torpedo bays.

745
00:37:25,917 --> 00:37:28,000
O'BRIEN:
Sir, let me
beam over.

746
00:37:28,041 --> 00:37:30,041
Try to talk to him.

747
00:37:30,083 --> 00:37:31,667
We served together a long time.

748
00:37:31,709 --> 00:37:34,250
When you've been through
what we have, you tend

749
00:37:34,291 --> 00:37:35,583
to get inside someone.

750
00:37:35,625 --> 00:37:36,959
He might listen.

751
00:37:37,000 --> 00:37:38,166
He'd never lower
his shields

752
00:37:38,208 --> 00:37:39,792
and allow you
to transport on board.

753
00:37:39,834 --> 00:37:42,750
The<i> Phoenix</i> is using
a high-energy sensor system.

754
00:37:42,792 --> 00:37:45,291
It cycles
every 5.5 minutes.

755
00:37:45,333 --> 00:37:46,792
Between cycles,
there's a window

756
00:37:46,834 --> 00:37:48,166
of a 50th of a second.

757
00:37:48,208 --> 00:37:50,583
Trust me.
I can get through.

758
00:37:50,625 --> 00:37:52,625
Make it so.

759
00:37:59,875 --> 00:38:01,959
(<i> doorbell chimes</i> )

760
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:04,041
Not now!

761
00:38:09,709 --> 00:38:11,083
I'm not armed.

762
00:38:11,125 --> 00:38:13,834
How the devil
did you get over here?

763
00:38:13,875 --> 00:38:16,917
I had the thought
that if we could talk

764
00:38:16,959 --> 00:38:19,959
we could figure a way
out of this mess.

765
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:21,709
The way out of this is clear.

766
00:38:21,750 --> 00:38:23,125
Talk to Picard.

767
00:38:23,166 --> 00:38:24,959
Get him to board the damn ship.

768
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:26,917
He won't do that, sir.

769
00:38:26,959 --> 00:38:29,709
But he'd turn his weapons
on a Federation starship

770
00:38:29,750 --> 00:38:30,917
to protect the enemy?

771
00:38:30,959 --> 00:38:32,625
I don't
believe it.

772
00:38:32,667 --> 00:38:33,625
He will.

773
00:38:33,667 --> 00:38:35,500
Count on it.

774
00:38:35,542 --> 00:38:39,417
What the hell has happened
to this war?

775
00:38:39,458 --> 00:38:42,166
Sir...

776
00:38:42,208 --> 00:38:45,208
there is no war.

777
00:38:45,250 --> 00:38:48,291
The war is over.

778
00:38:50,750 --> 00:38:53,041
You're wrong.

779
00:38:53,083 --> 00:38:55,709
The Cardassians live
to make war.

780
00:38:55,750 --> 00:38:58,667
That's what everybody thinks
about the enemy.

781
00:38:58,709 --> 00:39:01,750
That's probably what
they think about us.

782
00:39:01,792 --> 00:39:03,125
We're not
the same at all.

783
00:39:03,166 --> 00:39:05,542
We do not<i> start</i> wars.

784
00:39:07,500 --> 00:39:11,458
We do not make surprise
attacks on manned outposts.

785
00:39:11,500 --> 00:39:15,583
We do not butcher women and
children in their homes.

786
00:39:17,125 --> 00:39:19,041
Children...

787
00:39:20,792 --> 00:39:24,166
who never had the
chance to grow up.

788
00:39:30,583 --> 00:39:33,208
You were with me on Setlik.

789
00:39:33,250 --> 00:39:36,125
You saw
what they did.

790
00:39:36,166 --> 00:39:37,750
Yes, sir.

791
00:39:43,250 --> 00:39:45,125
What was the name
of that fellow

792
00:39:45,166 --> 00:39:47,417
who always hung around you
like a puppy?

793
00:39:48,583 --> 00:39:50,542
Will Kayden.

794
00:39:52,583 --> 00:39:54,166
Stompie.

795
00:39:54,208 --> 00:39:56,291
Stompie!

796
00:39:56,333 --> 00:39:59,458
Stompie!

797
00:39:59,500 --> 00:40:02,542
As cool under fire
as a mountain lake.

798
00:40:02,583 --> 00:40:04,542
Yes, sir.

799
00:40:10,375 --> 00:40:13,959
He died at Setlik,
didn't he?

800
00:40:14,000 --> 00:40:15,875
Yes, sir.

801
00:40:19,625 --> 00:40:22,500
What was that song of his?

802
00:40:22,542 --> 00:40:23,709
The one he always sang?

803
00:40:23,750 --> 00:40:25,375
The one I liked?

804
